commentBody:
@Wesley

It may be the first time you’ve seen it, but it’s the fifth time that it has appeared. 

<a href="https://www.xwordinfo.com/Finder?w=RITAORA" target="_blank">https://www.xwordinfo.com/Finder?w=RITAORA</a>

@DW

I want to ask the "easy" crowd...

Did you have CHARLIXCX at your disposal, or did you have to get it from what I thought were relatively difficult crosses, like  OSX and MIIS?

@Steve L

Ok.  

Then I contend that the difficulty of the puzzle came down entirely on whether or not one knew CHARLIXCX, or at least had an inkling there was a singer with an unusual first name and a three letter last name, two of which are "X".

@Francis

A gimme for me too. At first, I forgot that there's no E on the end of CHARLI, but spelling is often my biggest challenge. 

And yet... even with CHARLIXCX in place, that section of the puzzle was the hardest for me. I'll elaborate in a separate comment.

@SBK

Strange how I shield myself from parts of the world apparently without even thinking about.  I thought I was paying attention to the last campaign, but somehow I never got that tidbit.

MII is apparently a brand name?  I guess of an avatar creator?   I looked it up but it meant so little to me that I moved on immediately.

@Francis

Oddly, MII and OSX were gimmes, but I thought I had erred with the nonsensical IXCX ending, never having heard of the singer. I had to google JACCUSE and then I could suss out the rest.

I finished in just over Tuesday time because that  whole NW corner was a Natick, and I knew if I didn't look one thing up, I'd never finish. I picked the clue most likely to help (1D) , to give me the starts of all the acrosses, and then used logic to finish.

@B

I'm getting a real sense of deva ju.  

But is it still deja vu if it really did happen before?

@B

Exactly what I thought. 

(And the columnist is a she.)

@SP

I'd never heard of BEERDARTS myself. It sounds like the Worst Idea Ever.

Liked ANECDATA though. And I loved SISTERACT.

@Francis

CHARLI XCX was a gimme but I got stumped by C__T/B_ER/SNOCA_S.

This grid felt like the constructor started with a Monday puzzle but decided to submit it for Friday so they put in proper names and trivia in several places, and crossed them. I really hate such construction, and that's not too strong a word for what I'm feeling towards it.

@Ely Especially the complaint about too much US trivia. Why do a puzzle from a NYC newspaper if the trivia endemic to NYC is an annoyance and not an opportunity? 

Blah blah global reach blah blah international subscribers blah blah blah.

Today I was especially grateful that MIIS was stashed, UNSET, in my brain. Because I sure didn't know CHARLIXCX, but the name seemed possible for a current artist.

@MExpat, @Francis

Me three! I was so encouraged by the nice literary clues at first, only to wash up on the rocky shores of unforgiving pop trivia. Throw in a few product brand names I forgot decades ago or never knew and I wave the white flag of surrender. 

Fellow geezer and proud of it.

@Francis
country song for librarians!!!

(id probably listen...)

@Henry Su
ANNE RICE would have celebrated her 84th birthday this month, October 4. 

There will be an All Saints' Day tribute to her  at the Orpheum Theater in New Orleans, Saturday, November 1, 2025.

@Andrzej

As someone said the other day, you do live rent-free in a lot of brains this side of the ocean because I did think of you as I was wading through the trivia—ohh, Andrzej will hate this… 

I meant *that* side of the ocean. Yikes. On the mornings coffee isn’t strong enough, I forget I’m a temporary European.

@Sam Lyons

Is it not fascinating how our lives shape us and how some things become part of the very core of our identify even though they could have been so long ago? When my best childhood friend died recently I realized to what an incredible extent the person I am now is still that kid growing up in the mud and concrete wasteland of the Ursynów district of 1980s Warsaw. 

As for rent-free living in your heads - who could have imagined 40 years ago anybody would even hear about me across the ocean, let alone think about me - or my persona, at least? The world really is an intriguing place, and the ways in which it may surprise us are endless.

@Andrzej

I’m very sorry you’ve lost your old friend. It makes childhood memories very different, doesn’t it?

And yeah, I get it: Parts of me will always be a naive girl from Utah. My parents dragged me all over the world when I was a kid, and still it’s the hometown part that’s imprinted on me most deeply, most indelibly.

@Francis

I'm glad you got through it -- however it happened!  They weren't familiar even after the reveal so I was glad I hadn't given up too easily. 

I better start being nicer to the cosmos.... Or at least watch more Kosmos Kramer. 😏

@Joe

Every where I look today I see the seeds of classic country songs.  

You have the first two lines.  All you need is about six more, a chorus, and a melody and arrangement, which you might be able to buy online.

@Francis

The NYT seems to have some of the w0rst and most clu3less IT people there exist. This is their crowning achievement 🤷🏽

All we want is an edit button... I'd appreciate persistent nicknames and a searchable post database, too. But no! Let's do none of that, but let's spoil how the comments are displayed!

@Francis a decade or so ago, I participated in the "Numberplay" column in NYT, which had a robust & lively (and relatively small) community of participants with long & lively comment streams.

I ended up building an "enhancer" to the NYT comment system that numbered the comments, allowed people to reference numbered entries in replies (this was before threads), format math in LaTeX (it was a math column after all), include images, and even visualize the comment flow.

Alas it broke every time NYT upgraded the comment system. I did have some exchange with the NYT development team at some point ... they weren't horrible at the time, but not particularly supportive.

@Gary

Wow!  That's an interesting historical tidbit.  

And a great demonstration of how hard it can be to build software of other software, especially proprietary software.

@Jessica

I've been quoted (in jest) as saying that a male reaches menopause when their attraction to the females is so low that no female of child bearing age will look at them twice.  Some males go through menopause quite young.

Not nearly a comparison to the real thing, from what I understand.

@Andrzej

You're playing that little bit of the cliche of the tiny hints from a professor that changes their entire life, and the fate of the entire world, aren't you?

I play that at least twice a week.  (Emeritus version)

@Laney

"I had no foothold except CHARLIXCX"

And I think that's what makes this puzzle special:  the utterly even divide who knew that cold name, or at least had a significant part of it, and those for whom it was as foreign as...as foreign as...a foreign thing that you'd called "foreign" real soon.  Within five seconds or so.

@Dorothy

I understand your concern about stepping on a cultural land mine, but you should be aware that both sides are under that stress.

If each side would get their members to pull back a bit, we might not need to experience what could be coming.

@Helen Wright
Isn’t the name sort of confusing? „-pause“ usually denotes something finite, something where there’s a continuation afterwards. But what is the“meno“ that then continues?
And the clueing with the word „event“ was also misleading in a similar sense. Wouldn’t „phase“ or something similar be more apt?

@Ely
They do Ely, they do. Don’t know if you saw my post a few days ago, but my fool Shiba got into the alpaca field; after a little running and a lot of screaming from me, they realised they were considerably bigger than him and turned. You should have seen the look on his face; pure terror. Those girls have long legs that go in all directions. They got in a few kicks (at me!) before I hauled him out. He’s kept his distance since.

Is yours territorial around the home? Kobe is a lamb out and about, but a Cane Corso in disguise around the homestead. Nothing is getting through; the screaming, the biting of the fences if he can’t get at the postie/delivery driver/any human or dog in general. I mean, I’ll never be snuck up on, but dear lord the noise. We have builders in right now, who have to run the gauntlet every morning before he’ll let them in.

@Helen Wright
Bombay Sapphire was my all-time favorite gin before going alcohol free. Place a pint in front of me, and I may have to jump off the wagon to sample it.
We play bridge, and there's no alcohol during those 3 hour sessions. I'm curious as to what goes on during gin club gathering. Dare I ask? Maybe all the bridge rules would make better sense with some well-placed Bombay.

@Jerry
I lived not far from their distillery, they do great tours.
So, gin club; we take turns to choose 3 gins with a loose theme. Could be area, botanicals etc. We have one neat shot plus one with mixer, repeat three times, then keep at it till the bottles are empty. There are twelve of us, so it’s a fair amount of gin ingested. There may be singing, story telling and general jocularity. Then we roll home til next month.  Lovely.

@Leapfinger

I'm with you in the common usage. 

Though I bet someone could take the perspective that from person to person, injury to injury, physical or emotional, new  hip vs scraped knee, there may be a SCAR literally or figuratively that does not yet indicate a completely healed condition.

@Steve -- I see the distinction you're making, and would only say to guard against conflating healing and recovery.

That applies only to physical healing, of course; emotional being an entirely different horse and fire department.

Hoping every mother's child is well-healed both ways on this beautiful FreiDay!

@Shrike --- Interesting concept, and food for all kinds of thought... especially considering the associated nom de plume.

Of course, you're playing with words. Any injury to living tissue will never remain unchanged. It will try to heal as best it can and either succeed, and if that isn't possible to any real extent, it remains only  to deteriorate, to fester and perhaps to die. With some license, that can apply to other than physical wounds.

Just as the SCAB /SCAR discussion is playing with words

